The course is divided into three parts: poetry, novel, theatre. The first part focuses on the development of Renaissance poetry, the second on the emergence of naturalist novel and the third on the character of classicist theatre of the 17th c. The final part of the course briefly treats the different manifestations of the first person in texts.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to provide students with basic knowledge of the work of selected authors from 16th-19th century French literature and prepare students for future work with texts. The lecture course focuses on the development of different genres and asks broader questions about the literariness and representative and performative character of texts and its significance from a socio-historical perspective.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Students who have completed the course can analyse literary texts from the perspective of genre, critically evaluate different materials in literary history or criticism and develop their own relationships with texts. Students acquire the basic principles of composing argumentative texts in French (quoting, referencing, differentiating one's own arguments from the  material referred to) and primary skills of structuring their texts.
